    <!--                     SECTION THREE: CHORDS                       -->
    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

    <!-- Was !!! EMPTY !!! — written from context (chords) -->
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryDef_10">• A chord is a line segment with both endpoints on a circle.
\n • The diameter is the longest chord, passing through the center.
\n • Equal chords are chords of the same length within the same circle.</string>

    <!-- Q: Is the diameter the longest chord in a circle? Answer: True -->
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryDefQuestion_10">Is the diameter the longest chord in a circle?</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryDefAnswerOne_10">True</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryDefAnswerTwo_10">False</string>
    <!-- Only 2 answers for True/False — third answer intentionally removed -->
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryDefAnswerThree_10"></string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryDefCorrectAnswer_10">True</string>

    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryProperties_10">• The diameter is the longest chord.
\n • Equal chords create equal arcs.
\n • Diameter perpendicular to a chord bisects it.</string>

    <!-- Q: Does a diameter perpendicular to a chord bisect that chord? Answer: True -->
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryPropsQuestion_10">Does a diameter perpendicular to a chord bisect that chord?</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryPropsAnswerOne_10">True</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryPropsAnswerTwo_10">False</string>
    <!-- Only 2 answers for True/False — third answer intentionally removed -->
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryPropsAnswerThree_10"></string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryPropsCorrectAnswer_10">True</string>

    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryWorkedExamples_10">• Proof that a diameter perpendicular to a chord bisects it: draw radii to both chord endpoints, forming two right triangles. They are congruent by HL (equal hypotenuse = radius, shared leg = perpendicular), so the two halves of the chord are equal.
\n • A chord parallel to another chord is longer when it is closer to the center — proved by comparing the distances from the center to each chord using the perpendicular bisector.
\n • Equal chords in the same circle subtend equal arcs, shown by rotating the triangle formed by two radii and the chord onto the other chord.</string>

    <!-- Q: How many equal parts does a perpendicular diameter divide a chord into? Answer: 2 -->
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryWorkedExQuestion_10">Into how many equal parts does a diameter perpendicular to a chord divide it?</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryWorkedExAnswerOne_10">3</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryWorkedExAnswerTwo_10">4</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryWorkedExAnswerThree_10">2</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryWorkedExCorrectAnswer_10">2</string>

