    <!--             SECTION FOUR: INSCRIBED & CIRCUMSCRIBED POLYGONS    -->
    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

    <string name="SectionFourTheoryDef_10">• An inscribed polygon has all vertices on a circle.
\n • A circumscribed polygon has all sides tangent to a circle.
\n • Circles define these polygon relationships.</string>

    <!-- Q: Does an inscribed polygon have all its vertices on the circle? Answer: True -->
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryDefQuestion_10">Does an inscribed polygon have all its vertices on the circle?</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryDefAnswerOne_10">True</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryDefAnswerTwo_10">False</string>
    <!-- Only 2 answers for True/False — third answer intentionally removed -->
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryDefAnswerThree_10"></string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryDefCorrectAnswer_10">True</string>

    <string name="SectionFourTheoryProperties_10">• Every triangle has one inscribed and one circumscribed circle.
\n • For a quadrilateral, opposite angles sum 180° for a circumscribed circle.
\n • Equal opposite side sums allow an inscribed circle.</string>

    <!-- Q: In a cyclic quadrilateral, opposite angles sum to how many degrees? Answer: 180 -->
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryPropsQuestion_10">In a cyclic quadrilateral, opposite angles sum to how many degrees?</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryPropsAnswerOne_10">90</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryPropsAnswerTwo_10">360</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryPropsAnswerThree_10">180</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryPropsCorrectAnswer_10">180</string>

    <string name="SectionFourTheoryWorkedExamples_10">• Cyclic quadrilateral proof: opposite angles intercept arcs that together make a full circle (360°), so each pair of opposite inscribed angles intercepts supplementary arcs — their sum is 180°.
\n • Circumscribed quadrilateral proof: tangent segments from each vertex to the two adjacent tangency points are equal. Labelling them a, b, c, d around the quadrilateral shows AB + CD = BC + DA, proving equal opposite side sums.
\n • These two conditions — opposite angles summing to 180° and opposite side sums being equal — are the exact criteria for a quadrilateral to admit a circumscribed or inscribed circle respectively.</string>

    <!-- Q: How many circles does every triangle have (inscribed and circumscribed combined)? Answer: 2 -->
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryWorkedExQuestion_10">How many special circles (inscribed and circumscribed) does every triangle have in total?</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryWorkedExAnswerOne_10">1</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryWorkedExAnswerTwo_10">3</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryWorkedExAnswerThree_10">2</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryWorkedExCorrectAnswer_10">2</string>

