    <!--               SECTION FIVE: TRIANGLE CENTERS                    -->
    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryDef_10">• The centroid is where medians meet.
\n • The orthocenter is where altitudes intersect.
\n • Both are special triangle points.</string>

    <!-- Q: Where do the three medians of a triangle meet? Answer: centroid -->
    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryDefQuestion_10">What is the name of the point where all three medians of a triangle meet?</string>
    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryDefAnswerOne_10">centroid</string>
    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryDefAnswerTwo_10">orthocenter</string>
    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryDefAnswerThree_10">circumcenter</string>
    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryDefCorrectAnswer_10">centroid</string>

    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryProperties_10">• Medians meet at a point two-thirds from each vertex.
\n • Altitudes always meet at one point.
\n • Defines triangle centers and relations.</string>

    <!-- Q: The centroid divides each median in ratio from vertex to midpoint. Answer: 2/3 -->
    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryPropsQuestion_10">The centroid divides each median in what ratio (from vertex to centroid vs full median length)?</string>
    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryPropsAnswerOne_10">1/2</string>
    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryPropsAnswerTwo_10">2/3</string>
    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryPropsAnswerThree_10">3/4</string>
    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryPropsCorrectAnswer_10">2/3</string>

    <!-- Fixed typo: 10:1 ratio → 2:1 ratio -->
    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryWorkedExamples_10">• To construct a triangle given its three median lengths m1, m2, m3: build a triangle with sides (2/3)m1, (2/3)m2, (2/3)m3 — this is the medial triangle scaled from the centroid. Scale back by 3/2 to recover the original.
\n • Proof that the centroid divides each median in ratio 2:1: draw two medians and their intersection G. The triangles formed on either side of G share a vertex and have equal bases (midpoint construction), so by the midline theorem G is located 2/3 of the way from each vertex.
\n • The orthocenter, centroid, and circumcenter are collinear on the Euler line, with the centroid dividing the segment between the other two in ratio 2:1.</string>

    <!-- Q: The centroid divides each median in ratio 2:1 from vertex. What fraction from vertex is the centroid? Answer: 2/3 -->
    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryWorkedExQuestion_10">In the ratio 2:1 in which the centroid divides a median, what fraction of the full median length is the centroid from the vertex?</string>
    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryWorkedExAnswerOne_10">1/3</string>
    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryWorkedExAnswerTwo_10">1/2</string>
    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryWorkedExAnswerThree_10">2/3</string>
    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryWorkedExCorrectAnswer_10">2/3</string>

